const Q_ECONOMICS_2019_MODEL_I=[{"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the following is a correct characteristic of the advanced market capitalist economy</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">proper distribution of income</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a greater standard by the generality of the citizens</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it is not prone to economic uncertainties and political upheavals</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the rich getting richer and the poor getting poorer</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the correct characteristics of an advanced market capitalist economy is \"the rich getting richer and the poor getting poorer.\" In a market capitalist economy, where the means of production are primarily owned by private individuals or entities, there tends to be an unequal distribution of wealth and income. This characteristic often results in the concentration of wealth among a small portion of the population, leading to the rich getting richer. At the same time, those with fewer resources may struggle to improve their economic situation, resulting in the poor getting poorer. <br/>  <br/> It is important to note that this characteristic is not universally true for all market capitalist economies and can vary depending on various factors, including government policies, social safety nets, and economic conditions. Additionally, this characteristic is not necessarily exclusive to advanced market capitalist economies and can be observed in other economic systems as well.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC SYSTEMS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Kong earn $300 and pays $15 as tax while Y earns $100 and pays $6 as tax. This system could be described as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">proportional tax</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">progressive tax</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">competitive tax</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">regressive tax</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a regressive tax system, the lower-income earners pay a higher percentage of their income in taxes than the higher-income earners. This is because regressive taxes are typically flat taxes, meaning that they are applied to all incomes at the same rate. <br/>  <br/> In the example you provided, Kong pays a 5% tax rate ($15 / $300  x 100 ) , while Y pays a 6% tax rate ($6 / $100  x 100). This means that Y pays a higher percentage of his income in taxes than Kong, even though he earns less money. <br/>  <br/> Therefore, the answer is regressive tax.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC FINANCE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the theory of the firm, the curve used in the determination of profit level is?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the average fixed cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the marginal cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the average variable cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the average cost</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Profit maximization occurs when a firm produces at a level where marginal cost (MC) equals marginal revenue (MR). At this point, the firm is producing the quantity of goods or services that generates the highest level of profit. The MC curve provides information about the additional cost incurred when producing one more unit of output, and it is essential for profit-maximizing decisions. <br/>  <br/> While the average fixed cost (AFC), average variable cost (AVC), and average cost (AC) curves are important in cost analysis, they are not used directly in the determination of profit levels. Profit maximization focuses on the relationship between marginal cost and marginal revenue</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF COST AND REVENUE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the disadvantages of international trade is that it</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">encourage economic independence among nations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increases world output</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">promote self-reliance and satisfaction with only what can be produced internally</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">restricts spread of technical knowledge</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the disadvantages of international trade is that it promotes self-reliance and satisfaction with only what can be produced internally. This is because international trade can lead to the decline of domestic industries that are unable to compete with foreign producers. This can lead to unemployment and economic hardship in the affected countries.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL TRADE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A primary industry is concern with</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">clearing and cultivating of land only</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the operation of small scale enterprises</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the economic activities of primary</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">extraction of resources in their raw state</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A primary industry is concerned with the extraction of resources in their raw state. <br/>  <br/> Primary industries are the first stage in the production process, and they involve the extraction of raw materials from the natural environment. Examples of primary industries include agriculture, forestry, fishing, mining, and quarrying.</div>", "topic": "INDUSTRY AND INDUSTRIALIZATION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Labour productivity is defined as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Total level of output</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Average output</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Output per man/hour</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Marginal Output of labour</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Labor productivity is defined as output per unit of labor. It is a measure of how much output is produced by a worker in a given period of time. Labor productivity can be measured in terms of output per hour, output per day, or output per year. <br/>  <br/> The total level of output is the total amount of goods and services produced by an economy in a given period of time. Average output is the total output divided by the number of workers. Marginal output of labor is the additional output produced by one additional worker.</div>", "topic": "LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The institution established to enhance the activities of Nigeria's export is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Bank of Industry</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigerian Export and Import Bank</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria Export Promotion Council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Import Substitution Strategy</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The institution established to enhance the activities of Nigeria's export is the Nigeria Export Promotion Council (NEPC). <br/>  <br/> NEPC is the Federal Government of Nigeria's apex institution for the promotion, development and diversification of exports. It was established in 1976 and is headquartered in Abuja, with regional offices in each of the six geo-political zones.</div>", "topic": "BUSINESS ORGANIZATIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The principal national macro-economics goals include the following</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National goods and priorities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Full employment of the nation's productive inputs</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Acceptable levels of economics growth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Maximums levels of economic stability</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The best option is Full employment of the nation's productive inputs. <br/>  <br/> This is because full employment is essential for economic growth. When everyone who wants to work is able to find a job, businesses have more customers and can produce more goods and services. This leads to higher incomes and improved standards of living. <br/>  <br/> Full employment also helps to reduce poverty and social unrest. When people are unemployed, they are more likely to live in poverty and to be involved in crime. Full employment helps to create a more stable and prosperous society.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC GROWTH AND DEVELOPMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During a recession, an appropriate fiscal policy would be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a decrease in the monetary policy rate(MPR)</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an increase in taxes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an increase in government spending</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a decrease in the reserve requirement</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Fiscal policy is the use of government spending and taxation to influence the economy. During a recession, the economy is producing below its potential and unemployment is high. The goal of fiscal policy during a recession is to boost economic activity and reduce unemployment. <br/>  <br/> One way to boost economic activity is to increase government spending. When the government spends money, it injects money into the economy. This money can be used by businesses to invest and create jobs, or by consumers to buy goods and services. Both of these activities lead to increased economic activity.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC FINANCE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The monetary system that relates to double coincidence of wants is referred to as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the gold standard</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the cheque system</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">barter</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the commodity system</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a barter system, individuals exchange goods and services directly with each other without using money as an intermediary. However, for a trade to occur in a barter system, there must be a double coincidence of wants, meaning that both parties involved in the exchange must want what the other has to offer. This can be challenging, as it requires finding someone who not only has what you want but also wants what you have to trade. <br/>  <br/> The use of money as a medium of exchange overcomes the limitations of the barter system by providing a universally accepted and easily divisible means of trade.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF ECONOMICS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The market form in which there is only one producers is called</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monopsony</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">oligopoly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monopoly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">duopoly</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The market form in which there is only one producer is called a monopoly. In a monopoly, a single firm or producer has a dominant or exclusive position in the market, and it is the sole seller of a particular product or service with no close substitutes. This allows the monopoly firm to have significant control over pricing and market supply.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Resources are scarce in relation to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">choice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the demand for them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">limited wants</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their scale of preference</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">There are limited resources available to meet unlimited wants. This means that we have to make choices about how to use the resources that we have. We cannot have everything that we want, so we have to prioritize our wants and make choices based on our needs.</div>", "topic": "INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economics is a science which deals with</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the factors of production</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">oil exploration</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">allocation of scare resources</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the gross domestic product (GDP)</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economics is the social science that studies how people make decisions about how to allocate scarce resources. This includes decisions about how to produce, distribute, and consume goods and services. The distribution of limited resources is a central theme in economics, and economists have developed a variety of tools and theories to help us understand how resources are allocated in different markets and economies.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC SYSTEMS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the gains by member states of the Economic Community of West Africa State is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Monocultural dependency</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Trade creation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Trade inversion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economic independency</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the gains by member states of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) is trade creation. <br/>  <br/> Trade creation is the increase in trade between member states that results from the removal of trade barriers. When trade barriers are removed, goods and services can flow more freely between countries, which can lead to lower prices and increased competition. This can benefit consumers and businesses in all member states.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC INTEGRATION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Factors of production are said to be specified when</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they can be put to only one use in production</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they can be put to all uses in production</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they are used to analyze cost effective</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">none of the above</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Factors of production are said to be \"specified\" when they can be put to all uses in production. In other words, specified factors of production are versatile and can be used in various ways to produce different goods and services. This flexibility in using factors of production is a key concept in economics, as it allows for efficient allocation and utilization of resources to meet diverse production needs. So, the correct answer is: \"they can be put to all uses in production.\"</div>", "topic": "FACTORS OF PRODUCTION AND THEIR THEORIES"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Stock and Share as well as Bonds are examples of instrument used in the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">commodity by the market</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">capital market</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">money market</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">security market</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The capital market is a financial market where long-term securities, such as stocks and bonds, are traded. Investors in the capital market are typically seeking to invest their money for a longer period of time, and they are willing to take on more risk in order to potentially earn higher returns.</div>", "topic": "FINANCIAL INSTITUTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following reasons could induce a manufacturer to bypass the wholesaler in the distribution chain</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To provide the quantity needed by retailers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To collect useful information on his product</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To provide warehousing facilities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To violate government regulation on distribution</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A manufacturer may bypass the wholesaler in the distribution chain to provide the quantity needed by retailers. <br/>  <br/> Wholesalers typically buy goods in bulk from manufacturers and then sell them in smaller quantities to retailers. This can be inefficient for manufacturers who need to provide retailers with specific quantities of goods. By bypassing the wholesalers, manufacturers can ensure that retailers get the exact quantities of goods they need.</div>", "topic": "DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If the fixed cost is #600.00, variable cost is #400.00 and total output 100. What is the average cost?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#11.00</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#10.00</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#12.00</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#20.00</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Total Cost = Fixed Cost + Variable Cost <br/>  <br/> Total Cost = #600.00 + #400.00 <br/>  <br/> Total Cost = #1,000.00 <br/>  <br/> Now, plug these values into the formula for average cost: <br/> Average Cost = (#1,000.00) / (100) <br/>  <br/> Average Cost = #10.00</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF COST AND REVENUE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">NON -Specific factor of production is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">machine</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">factory building</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unskilled labour</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">farm land</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The non-specific factor of production is unskilled labor. While machines, factory buildings, and farm land are specific factors of production as they are specialized and used for specific purposes, unskilled labor refers to a general or non-specific type of labor that can be utilized in various industries or sectors without requiring specific skills or training.</div>", "topic": "FACTORS OF PRODUCTION AND THEIR THEORIES"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of these factors does not determine the level of aggregate savings?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the level of income</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the size of the population</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">income distribution</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the rate of interest</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Aggregate savings primarily depend on factors such as the level of income, income distribution, and the rate of interest. These factors influence how much individuals and households save out of their disposable income. Population size, on its own, does not directly determine the level of savings; it is the factors related to income and the financial environment that are more directly linked to savings behavior. <br/>  <br/> While population size can indirectly affect savings through its impact on income distribution or other economic factors, it is not a direct determinant of aggregate savings.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL INCOME"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following definition of Economics is the most generally accepted?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">science that deals with production</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">science that deals with distribution</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">science that studies mankind</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">science which studies human behaviour as a relationship between ends and scare means which have alternative uses</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Economics is the science which studies human behavior as a relationship between ends and scarce means which have alternative uses.\" This definition captures the essence of economics by emphasizing the study of human behavior, the allocation of scarce resources, and the concept of trade-offs and opportunity costs. It is widely recognized and used by economists to describe the field of economics.</div>", "topic": "INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When 20 units of output is produce at #18 per unit, then TC will be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#360</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#300</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#460</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#400</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To calculate the TC, we use the formular  <br/>  <br/>  =  20 x 18 <br/>  <br/> = 360</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF COST AND REVENUE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The basis for all economic activities is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">scarcity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">poverty</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">industrial expansion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">economic development</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The basis for all economic activities is scarcity. Scarcity is the fundamental concept in economics that refers to the limited availability of resources (such as land, labor, capital, and natural resources) in comparison to the unlimited wants and needs of society. Because resources are limited, individuals, businesses, and governments must make choices about how to allocate these resources to meet their needs and wants.</div>", "topic": "INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Decreasing returns to scale implies that if all factors of production are doubled, output will be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">more than doubled</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">less than doubled</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">doubled</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mone of the above</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Decreasing returns to scale occurs when the output from a production process increases at a slower rate than the increase in the inputs. This means that if you double all of the inputs, the output will not double. It will increase, but by a smaller amount. <br/>  <br/> There are a number of reasons why decreasing returns to scale might occur. One reason is that as the scale of production increases, it becomes more difficult to coordinate and manage the production process. Another reason is that as the scale of production increases, it becomes more difficult to find and acquire the necessary inputs. <br/>  <br/> Decreasing returns to scale can have a number of implications for businesses. One implication is that it can make it difficult for businesses to grow. If a business needs to double its output in order to meet demand, it may not be able to do so without incurring higher costs. This can make it difficult for the business to compete with other businesses that are able to achieve economies of scale.</div>", "topic": "FACTORS OF PRODUCTION AND THEIR THEORIES"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The theoretical basis for international trade is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">international co-operation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exchange between countries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">absolute advantage</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">comparative advantage</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Comparative advantage is a more nuanced concept that was developed by David Ricardo in his book On the Principles of Political Economy and Taxation. It states that a country has a comparative advantage in the production of a good if it can produce that good at a lower opportunity cost than any other country. Opportunity cost is the cost of giving up something in order to get something else. <br/>  <br/> In other words, comparative advantage means that a country should specialize in the production of goods that it can produce relatively cheaply, and import goods that it can produce relatively expensively. This is because specialization and trade allow countries to produce more goods and services overall, and to enjoy a higher standard of living.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL TRADE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economics can be defined as </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reduction in spending in the face of competing alternatives</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">allocation of resources to alternative uses</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">economic behaviour of small units like the household and the firm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the study of economic aggregates like inflation and national income</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economics can be defined as the study of how people make choices under scarcity. It is the study of how individuals, businesses, governments, and societies allocate scarce resources to meet their wants and needs.</div>", "topic": "INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a command economy, resource allocation is managed primarily by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">large corporations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">competitive markets</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">labour unions</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">central planning</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a command economy, resource allocation is managed primarily by \"central planning.\" In such an economic system, the government or a central authority has a significant role in determining what goods and services will be produced, how they will be produced, and for whom they will be produced. This stands in contrast to market economies, where resource allocation is primarily driven by competitive markets and private individuals or businesses making decisions based on supply and demand.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC SYSTEMS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the graph below, FG indicates <br/>  <img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/></div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Excess demand</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Excess supply</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Equilibrium quantity supplied</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Equilibrium quantity demanded</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the graph provided above, FG should represent excess supply, not excess demand. This is because FG is above the equilibrium price. At a price above the equilibrium price, the quantity supplied is greater than the quantity demanded.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF DEMAND"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During the era of barter, money was generally in form of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">coins</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">notes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">commodities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">precious metals</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a barter system, people exchanged goods and services directly, and the medium of exchange was typically physical items or commodities that had intrinsic value and were mutually accepted as valuable for trade. These commodities could include items like livestock, grains, spices, or other goods that had utility and could serve as a medium of exchange in the absence of a formal currency. This form of barter money was based on the concept of the double coincidence of wants, where both parties in a trade had to want what the other had to offer.</div>", "topic": "MONEY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following reasons could induce a manufacturer to bypass the wholesaler in the distribution chain</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To provide the quantity needed by retailers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To collect useful information on his product</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To provide warehousing facilities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To violate government regulation on distribution</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A manufacturer may bypass the wholesaler in the distribution chain to provide the quantity needed by retailers. <br/>  <br/> Wholesalers typically buy goods in bulk from manufacturers and then sell them in smaller quantities to retailers. This can be inefficient for manufacturers who need to provide retailers with specific quantities of goods. By bypassing the wholesalers, manufacturers can ensure that retailers get the exact quantities of goods they need.</div>", "topic": "DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The World Trade Organization (WTO) is tasked with:</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">advancing global economic modernization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stabilizing and harmonizing oil prices</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ensuring equitable participation of nations in trade</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reducing barriers to international trade and investment</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The primary goal of the WTO is to facilitate and liberalize international trade. It aims to reduce or eliminate various barriers to trade, including tariffs, quotas, and other restrictions, in order to promote a more open and predictable trading system. While the WTO does contribute to global economic considerations, its main focus is on trade-related issues and negotiations.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL TRADE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following functions of money is worst affected by persistent inflation?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">medium of exchange</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unit of account</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">store of value</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">measure of value</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When there is persistent inflation, the value of money erodes over time. This means that the purchasing power of money decreases, and the same amount of money can buy fewer goods and services in the future than it could in the past. As a result, money becomes a less effective store of value because its real value diminishes.</div>", "topic": "INFLATION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Trade takes place because of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inefficiency in production</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">comparative advantage</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">marginal utility</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">opportunity cost</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Comparative advantage is a fundamental economic concept that suggests that individuals, businesses, or countries should specialize in producing the goods or services in which they have a comparative advantage, meaning they can produce those items at a lower opportunity cost compared to others. By trading with others who have different comparative advantages, all parties involved can benefit by obtaining goods and services at a lower overall cost than if they tried to produce everything themselves. Comparative advantage is a driving force behind international trade and specialization in the production of goods and services. While factors like inefficiency in production, marginal utility, and opportunity cost are related to trade decisions, comparative advantage is the central concept that explains why trade occurs.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL TRADE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A country achieves economic development when there is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an increase in military expenditure</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an increase in capacity utilization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a sustained increase in per capita income, accompanied by positive changes in standard of living</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an even distribution of goods and services</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economic development is a complex process that involves many factors, including economic growth, industrialization, and social progress. There is no single definition of economic development, but it is generally understood to mean a sustained improvement in the standard of living of a country's citizens. <br/>  <br/> Of the factors mentioned, a sustained increase in per capita income, accompanied by positive changes in standard of living is the most important indicator of economic development. This means that people in the country are getting richer and their quality of life is improving. This can be measured by things like life expectancy, literacy rates, and access to healthcare and education.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC GROWTH AND DEVELOPMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The majority advantage of pubic corporation is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stability</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inability to easily raised fund</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">service oriented policy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">its ability to monopolized production</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Public corporations are owned by the government and are not subject to the same market forces as private corporations. This means that they are less likely to go bankrupt or be acquired by another company. They also have access to government funding, which can help them to weather economic downturns.</div>", "topic": "BUSINESS ORGANIZATIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the effects of an increased minimum wage in Nigeria is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to create voluntary unemployment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to decrease the wage rate</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to increase the level of unemployment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to create involuntary unemployment</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the effects of an increased minimum wage in Nigeria is to increase the level of unemployment. <br/>  <br/> -   Voluntary unemployment occurs when people choose not to work because they are either unwilling to work or they believe that they cannot find a job that meets their expectations. <br/> -   Involuntary unemployment occurs when people are willing and able to work but they cannot find a job. <br/>  <br/> When the minimum wage is increased, it can lead to involuntary unemployment. This is because some businesses may not be able to afford to pay their workers the new minimum wage. As a result, they may lay off workers or hire fewer workers. This can lead to an increase in the level of unemployment.</div>", "topic": "LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Study the diagram below and answer the questions. <br/> <img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/>  <br/> In the diagram above, the equilibrium price is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OQ<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">o</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OQ<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">o</span>P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OP<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">o</span></div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The equilibrium price is the price at which the quantity demanded of a good or service is equal to the quantity supplied of that good or service. <br/>  <br/> In the diagram above, the demand curve is D and the supply curve is S. The equilibrium price and quantity are OPo and OQo, respectively. <br/>  <br/> At the equilibrium price, the quantity demanded and the quantity supplied are equal. This means that there is no shortage or surplus of the good or service.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> Study the diagram below and answer the questions. <br/> <img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> At price OP<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">demand exceeds supply</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">supply exceeds demand</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">demand equals supply</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OQ<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">I</span> is the quantity demanded</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">At price OP2, demand exceeds supply. <br/>  <br/> This can be seen from the diagram, where the quantity demanded at price OP2 (OQ2) is greater than the quantity supplied at price OP2 (OQ1). <br/>  <br/> When demand exceeds supply, there is a shortage of the good or service. This can lead to rationing, black markets, and other problems.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a capitalist economy, the economic problem of what goods to produce is decided mainly by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">shadow prices</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">profit level</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">relative prices</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a central planner</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The economic problem of what goods to produce in a capitalist economy is decided mainly by relative prices. <br/>  <br/> In a capitalist economy, businesses are free to produce whatever goods and services they think will be profitable. The prices of goods and services are determined by the interaction of supply and demand. Businesses will produce more of the goods and services that are in high demand and low supply, and they will produce less of the goods and services that are in low demand and high supply. <br/>  <br/> The profit level is also a factor in determining what goods to produce in a capitalist economy. Businesses will only produce goods and services if they think they can make a profit. However, the profit level is not the only factor that businesses consider. They will also consider the relative prices of different goods and services. <br/>  <br/> Shadow prices are not used to determine what goods to produce in a capitalist economy. Shadow prices are hypothetical prices that are used in economic planning. They are not used in the real market economy. <br/>  <br/> A central planner is not used to determine what goods to produce in a capitalist economy. A central planner is a person or group of people who control the economy. They decide what goods and services will be produced, how they will be produced, and who will get them. Central planners are not used in capitalist economies.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC SYSTEMS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2019 Model I>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If the demand for one commodity includes demand for another, it is said to be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">complementary demand</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">competitive demand</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">composite demand</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">derived demand</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Complementary demand exists between two goods that are used together. For example, the demand for cars and gasoline is complementary demand. If the demand for cars increases, the demand for gasoline will also increase.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF DEMAND"}];
